latestPosts.caption:
Posted @withregram • @verveindia “We want people to understand that though we may look different, our ethos is the same. The more this is normalised, we could break the stereotypes associated with this region. Gen Z here, too, has the same relationship with fashion as teens in any other city, it’s just that the interpretations and influence of subcultures are diverse.” Photographer Suraj Nongmaithem (@shutterbug_nong) brings together three long-time friends in a “visual poem” that amplifies the unique fashion aesthetic of young North-Eastern Indians. But from beneath the surface of the images emerges a deeper reflection on belonging and self-expression. 

Kenny (@ken_rupreo) and Sen (@sen_hmt), both from Nagaland, moved to the hilly capital of Meghalaya, the melting pot of the East, where they eventually met each other and @nafisa__31 (who grew up there) through their common love of music. In Nongmaithem’s photoessay, they collaborated with stylist @robertson_lyngdoh_, and the result is a stunning series that invites the viewer to engage with the juxtaposition of history and contemporary culture. In it, traditional sartorial heritages mix with a global and modern style sensibility, and the models’ identities are reflected as much in geometric-print sweaters, floral Peter Pan collar shirts and berry-hued corduroys – all thrifted, vintage or borrowed – as they are in pastel Manipuri saris and tribal Naga shawls. “Bollywood played no role whatsoever, and we had Western influences or our indigenous roots to turn to. Children from a young age are taught to dress well and look presentable, and as one goes through the different stages of life, fashion becomes like a second skin. I love that sense of freedom to express one’s style,” says Nafisa.  Full story at the link in bio
 
Text by: Mahima Shukla
Photographed by: Suraj Nongmaithem
